Here is a little video I put together of my spider spaces over the years. I like seeing how things evolved as I learned and gain more experience over time. 

Recently I've been working on the latest iteration of my spider room while also working on getting over my posting fear and rejoining the hobby. I've been reminiscing a bit while sorting through old content and thinking about my old rooms. I've kept spiders as pets my entire life and I started keeping tarantulas around 2007. I didn't get my first dedicated room until 2012. Renting, I always had to hide my collection & Nashville rent started to skyrocket so I found myself in a tiny apartment where I hid all of my arachnids in a bathroom closet. It was very humid in there so I couldn't risk buying anything new because when I first moved in I lost a few of them from it. I laid low for a few years so I could save money to buy a home. Finally in 2020 I did just that! No more hiding my animals & dealing with the stress of it all. I finally have a room I can do whatever I want with! Well, around that time I developed a posting fear. All the negativity everywhere really got to me. Everyone attacking everyone, even over the littlest things. I could barely post on my personal page. Answering spider questions was torcher, even responding to texts from my friends was extremely hard. Add a little sprinkle of adhd, anxiety, & depression on top and all my confidence was shot. My spider room was a wreck, like a bomb went off. I attempted to rearrange & clean it but to no avail. 3 years have gone by, I was almost going to sell the rest of my arachnids. People were even asking for lists. Thankfully I have a really incredible boyfriend who has really helped push and support me this past year. I quit smoking, I started seeing a therapist, I got re-medicated for the first time since high school, etc. He knows how important arachnids have been to me all my life and didn't want to see me give up my passion. I got myself some new arachnids, and we have started working on making my room functional like I've always wanted. I'm coming back & I'm excited for bigger & better things this time around. 😊❤️
